        "content": "<p>I've got a supposedly rare issue here. With dma_fences, we have backend callbacks invoked by C. In our Rust code, we want to access Rust data, but the callbacks only get C data. You can access that data, if its in the same chunk of memory as the C type, since you can then do <code>container_of</code>.</p>\n<p>I've got <a href=\"https://gitlab.freedesktop.org/pstanner/linux-drm-work/-/blob/jobqueue-jobqueue-rfc-v3-3/rust/kernel/sync/dma_fence.rs?ref_type=heads#L89\">this</a> struct, on which you can <a href=\"https://gitlab.freedesktop.org/pstanner/linux-drm-work/-/blob/jobqueue-jobqueue-rfc-v3-3/rust/kernel/sync/dma_fence.rs?ref_type=heads#L137\">create</a> other structs which contain their own data with their own generic.</p>\n<p>Now what I would like to do is to get my <code>FenceCtx</code> struct</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Rust\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"k\">unsafe</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">fn</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">raw_fence_to_fctx</span><span class=\"o\">&lt;'</span><span class=\"na\">a</span><span class=\"o\">&gt;</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"n\">ptr</span><span class=\"p\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">*</span><span class=\"k\">mut</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">bindings</span><span class=\"p\">::</span><span class=\"n\">dma_fence</span><span class=\"p\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kp\">&amp;</span><span class=\"o\">'</span><span class=\"na\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nc\">Self</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span>\n<span class=\"w\">            </span><span class=\"kd\">let</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">opaque_fence</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Opaque</span><span class=\"p\">::</span><span class=\"n\">cast_from</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"n\">ptr</span><span class=\"p\">);</span>\n\n<span class=\"w\">            </span><span class=\"c1\">// SAFETY: Safe due to the function's overall safety requirements.</span>\n<span class=\"w\">            </span><span class=\"kd\">let</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">fence_ptr</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">unsafe</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">crate</span><span class=\"p\">::</span><span class=\"n\">container_of</span><span class=\"o\">!</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"n\">opaque_fence</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Fence</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">inner</span><span class=\"p\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">};</span>\n\n<span class=\"w\">            </span><span class=\"kd\">let</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">fence_data_ptr</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">unsafe</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">crate</span><span class=\"p\">::</span><span class=\"n\">container_of</span><span class=\"o\">!</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"n\">opaque_fence</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">DriverFenceData</span><span class=\"o\">&lt;</span><span class=\"n\">F</span><span class=\"o\">&gt;</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">inner</span><span class=\"p\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">};</span>\n\n<span class=\"w\">            </span><span class=\"kd\">let</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">fence_data</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">unsafe</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">&amp;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">*</span><span class=\"n\">fence_data_ptr</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">};</span>\n\n<span class=\"w\">            </span><span class=\"c1\">// SAFETY: Safe due to the function's overall safety requirements.</span>\n<span class=\"w\">            </span><span class=\"kd\">let</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">fctx</span><span class=\"p\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kp\">&amp;</span><span class=\"nc\">Self</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">unsafe</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">&amp;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">*</span><span class=\"n\">fence_data</span><span class=\"p\">.</span><span class=\"n\">fctx</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">};</span>\n\n<span class=\"w\">            </span><span class=\"n\">fctx</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"p\">}</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>What ultimately shall be done is:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Cast / container_of  from a C <code>dma_fence</code> to a <code>Fence</code></li>\n<li>Cast / container_of from <code>Fence</code> to <code>DriverFenceData</code> – which depends on generic parameters</li>\n<li>Use the <a href=\"https://gitlab.freedesktop.org/pstanner/linux-drm-work/-/blob/jobqueue-jobqueue-rfc-v3-3/rust/kernel/sync/dma_fence.rs?ref_type=heads#L271\">rawptr</a> to access the FenceCtx, whose data I need</li>\n</ol>\n<p>IOW, I need access to the generic data type to do the cast.</p>\n<p>A <code>DmaFenceCtx</code> gets fully typed at creation. That works fine.</p>\n<p>The big question I now have is:<br>\n<strong>How can I obtain the data type from a C callback to do my cast / container_of?</strong></p>\n<p>It turns out it is strictly necessary to actually pass to each method the <code>self</code> parameter, which I ultimately cannot obtain from <code>extern \"C\" fn get_driver_name()</code></p>\n<p>How do I solve that problem idiomatically, where should I get the type information from?</p>",
